text:
JEANNE MOOS: It's your
move Mr President.

Whether it's a
glass or a coaster,

President Trump has a habit
of moving things a few inches
here, a few inches there.

A viewer alerted Jimmy Kimmel
to the president's quirk.

JIMMY KIMMEL: He's more
of a mover than a shaker.

JEANNE MOOS: Moving
individual items

and even an entire place
setting, apparently
seeking the sweet spot.

- General counsel
and public policy--

JEANNE MOOS: A
shorter compilation

circulated online, leading
to comments like, "This
is desktop manspreading.

He's marking his territory and
trying to intimidate others
with the space he takes up."

The President's
moves inspired web
gags and arm chair psychology.

"He thinks he's the
master of everything.
This is mind to touch."
[applause]

JIMMY KIMMEL: All I have to
say is I hope the new health
care plan covers OCD because--

JEANNE MOOS: OK, so
everyone has an opinion.
But what's a professional think?
A professor of psy--
[can clatters] --chology.

While declining to diagnose,
professor Kevin Vulcan

weighed in on what may be
behind this type of behavior.

KEVIN VULCAN: They're feelings
some anxiety about something

and so they control things,
they move things around,
they make lists--

JEANNE MOOS: Or more likely,
the professor says, in someone
with a narcissistic profile--

KEVIN VULCAN: They're
just really bored.

They get bored really
easily, especially when the
conversation is not about them.

JEANNE MOOS: Internet
posters likewise

couldn't resist moving things,
like the President's head,

replacing it with a cartoon
called Business Cat,
and adding a soundtrack.

[MUSIC - WILL I AM, "I LIKE TO
 MOVE IT"]
You like to move it!
I like to move it, move it.
I like to move it, move it.
I like to move it, move it.
You like to move it!

JEANNE MOOS: Funny,
President Trump

doesn't seem like the
type to be a paper pusher.
Jeanne Moos, CNN, New York.
